# Q10) Information Available in Continuous Random Variables

We are given:

T ~ N(0,1),  P ~ N(0,4), independent

Joint density:
f(T,P) = (1 / 4π) exp( -t²/2 - p²/8 )

X(T,P) = T
Y(T,P) = (T,P)

---

# 1) Probability Space

Ω = ℝ²
𝒜 = Borel σ-algebra on ℝ²
P induced by density f(T,P)

---

# 2) σ(X)

X = T only

σ(X) = σ(T)
→ all events depending only on T
→ sets of form B × ℝ

---

# 3) σ(Y)

Y = (T,P)

σ(Y) = σ(T,P)
= full Borel σ-algebra on ℝ²

---

# 4) Relation

σ(X) ⊂ σ(Y)

Reason: any event about T is also an event in (T,P)

Conclusion:
Y contains more information than X

---

# 5) Marginal of X

X ~ N(0,1)

fX(t) = (1/√(2π)) exp(-t²/2)

---

# 6) Marginal of Y

Since independent:

fY(t,p) = fT(t) fP(p)

= (1 / 4π) exp( -t²/2 - p²/8 )

---

# 7) Probabilities

P(X ≤ 0) = 1/2

P(X > 1) = 1 - Φ(1) ≈ 0.1587

P(Y ∈ (-∞,0] × ℝ)
= P(T ≤ 0) = 1/2

P(Y ∈ [-1,1] × [-2,2])
= P(-1≤T≤1) × P(-2≤P≤2)
≈ (0.6826)(0.9545) ≈ 0.651

---

# 8) Conditional distribution X | Y=(t,p)

From Y we know T exactly

So:

X = t with probability 1

→ deterministic (Dirac delta)

---

# 9) Conditional distribution Y | X = t

Given T=t:

P ~ N(0,4)

So:

Y | X=t = (t, P)

---

# 10) Interpretation

Condition on X:
→ only temperature known

Condition on Y:
→ temperature + pressure known

So Y gives full system information

---

# 11) Measurability

X = π₁(Y), where π₁(t,p)=t

Thus:

X is a function of Y
⇒ X is measurable w.r.t σ(Y)

---

# 12) Python Visualization

```python
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.stats import norm

# Grid for joint density
t = np.linspace(-4, 4, 200)
p = np.linspace(-8, 8, 200)
T, P = np.meshgrid(t, p)

# Joint density
f = (1/(4*np.pi)) * np.exp(-T**2/2 - P**2/8)

plt.figure(figsize=(6,5))
plt.contourf(T, P, f, levels=50)
plt.title("Joint Density f(T,P)")
plt.xlabel("T")
plt.ylabel("P")
plt.colorbar()
plt.show()

# Marginal density of X
plt.figure()
plt.plot(t, norm.pdf(t), label="f_X(t)")
plt.title("Marginal Density of X")
plt.xlabel("t")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

# Illustration of sigma-algebras
# Vertical strips represent σ(X) (depends only on T)
plt.figure(figsize=(6,5))
plt.contourf(T, P, f, levels=20, alpha=0.6)

for val in [-2, -1, 0, 1, 2]:
    plt.axvline(val, linestyle='--')

plt.title("σ(X): Vertical strips (depends only on T)")
plt.xlabel("T")
plt.ylabel("P")
plt.show()
```

